## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

This is our go-to methodology to develop hypotheses for any experiment. Usually, we develop one abstract version of the hypothesis, in the form of a causal chain, that is later express in concrete experimental or intervention oriented form. You car read about this here: https://www.py.undp.org/content/paraguay/es/home/blog/2020/Constructing-Hypotheses-for-Development.html

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

It helped us simplify how we communicate expected impact and, also, it has helped the office develop ways to summarize what different projects are about, communicating better their specifi experience firts, and later abstracting that experience into something that resembles a theory of the change they are seeing or expecting to see. It is key to isolate specific phenomena or variables where we can design an develop an experimental intervention.  
  
The main weakness would be that, sometimes, it could lead to oversimplification if we loose sight of the bigger picture in which our hypotheses are integrated, or if we are not actually aware of the different variables that we may be leaving out for the sake identifying a key area of intervention.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)

Simplifying how we develop and express theories of change in ways that can easily move us toward experimentation

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?

1. Define your hypothesis in if/then fashion.  
  
2. List your variables and start your causal chain with just one independent and one dependent variable.  
  
3. Agument your causal chain with intermediary causes/effects and conditional variables.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)

Understanding of causal inference.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?

Simplifying how we develop and express theories of change in ways that can easily move us toward experimentation.
